properties.SQL Pre-Query:
CREATE OR REPLACE TABLE STAGING_${name:toUpper()} AS
SELECT * EXCLUDE (__ROW_NUMBER)
FROM (
    SELECT
        s.*,
        ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY ${#{'Object Identifier Resolution'}:equals("CASE_INSENSITIVE"):ifElse('"ID"', '"Id"')} 
            ORDER BY ${#{'Object Identifier Resolution'}:equals("CASE_INSENSITIVE"):ifElse(${timestampField:replaceEmpty("SystemModstamp"):toUpper()}, ${timestampField:replaceEmpty("SystemModstamp"):append('"'):prepend('"')})} DESC)
        AS __ROW_NUMBER
    FROM STAGING_${name:toUpper()} s
) AS DEDUPED
WHERE __ROW_NUMBER = 1;

parameters.description: The database where data will be persisted. It must already exist in Snowflake
parameters.name: Destination Database

parameters.description: The schema where data will be persisted. It must already exist in Snowflake
parameters.name: Destination Schema

parameters.description: Determines if schema / table / column names are treated as case-sensitive or case-insensitive. One of: CASE_INSENSITIVE / CASE_SENSITIVE. Please note that changing this parameter value will require to clear the state and do a full reload of all objects.
parameters.name: Object Identifier Resolution

parameters.description: Snowflake account name formatted as [organization-name]-[account-name] where data will be persisted
parameters.name: Snowflake Account Identifier

parameters.description: Using SNOWFLAKE_MANAGED will make use of the Snowflake managed token associated with the specified Snowflake Runtime Role. If using Openflow BYOC, it is also possible to use KEY_PAIR in order to specify a specific user and role via a cusom Key Pair.
parameters.name: Snowflake Authentication Strategy

parameters.description: The RSA private key which is used for authentication. The RSA key must be formatted according to PKCS8 standards and have standard PEM headers and footers. Note that either Snowflake Private Key File or Snowflake Private Key must be defined
parameters.name: Snowflake Private Key

parameters.description: The file that contains the RSA Private Key used for authentication to Snowflake, formatted according to PKCS8 standards and having standard PEM headers and footers. The header line starts with -----BEGIN PRIVATE
parameters.name: Snowflake Private Key File

parameters.description: The password associated with the Snowflake Private Key File
parameters.name: Snowflake Private Key Password

parameters.description: Snowflake Role used during query execution

parameters.description: Qualified name of the Salesforce instance. This is usually something like: myCompany.my.salesforce.com
parameters.name: Salesforce Instance

parameters.description:
Defines the strategy to adopt when a column should be removed in the destination table based on the latest received schema. Three possible values: "Drop Column", "Rename Column", "Ignore Column".
- Drop Column - Drop the column from the Snowflake table
- Rename Column - Rename the column in the Snowflake table
- Ignore Column - Ignore the column, leaving it as is in the Snowflake table
parameters.name: Column Removal Strategy

parameters.description: Comma-separated list of objects to offload from Salesforce, or regular expression to apply against all existing objects. If left empty, all objects will be offloaded. This is not recommended as there are usually thousands of objects in a Salesforce instance. Example: Account, Opportunity, Contact
parameters.name: Filter

parameters.description: If set to a value other than None, the initial data load will be split into multiple jobs based on this interval. On the first run for an object, the connector will query Salesforce to find the oldest record and use that as the starting point. Each subsequent job will query the next time chunk until caught up to the current time. This is useful for large datasets where loading all historical data in a single query may timeout or exceed API limits. Once caught up, the processor will continue with normal incremental offload behavior. Should be set with one of: NONE, MONTHLY, QUARTERLY, YEARLY.
parameters.name: Initial Load Chunking

parameters.description: A JSON specifying which fields and field patterns should be included or excluded, per Salesforce object. Takes the form of an array with one item per object, e.g. [ {"objectType":"Account", "includedPattern":".*name"} ] - this will include all fields that end with 'name' in the 'Account' Salesforce object ; e.g. [ {"objectType":"Account", "included": ["Id", "Name", "Revenue"]} ] - this will include the fields Id, Name and Revenue in the 'Account' Salesforce object. excluded/excludedPattern are also available for configuring the filters.
parameters.name: Object Fields Filter JSON

parameters.description: Suffix added to the column name when the parameter "Column Removal Strategy" is set to "Rename Column"
parameters.name: Removed Column Name Suffix

parameters.description: Frequency at which the connector will check for updates in Salesforce for configured objects via the Filter parameter
parameters.name: Run Schedule
